&lt;h2 id="math">Math&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>You start and end math using dollar signs. If you use on, you get inline
math, and if you use two, you get &amp;ldquo;display&amp;rdquo; math, which means you get the math
on a single line and centered.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This is inline math: $\int_a^b x,\mathrm{d}x$.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This is display math:
$$\sum_{j=1}^N \frac{1}{j^2}$$&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Pandoc supports a large subset of math you can write in LaTeX.
For example, here is more complex equation.
$$
d(i,j) = \begin{cases}
,i &amp;amp; j = 0 \
,j &amp;amp; i = 0 \
,\min\begin{cases}
d(i-1,j-1) + \mathrm{1}(i\neq j) \
d(i,j-1) + 1 \
d(i-1,j) + 1
\end{cases} &amp;amp; i&amp;gt;0,j&amp;gt;0
\end{cases}
$$&lt;/p>
